did.head: DESCRIPTIVE SUMMARY
did.repository: Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections, Cornell University Library
did.abstract: Includes correspondence, news press releases, notes, publicity material, newspaper clippings, distribution lists, administrative files, photographs, biographies, and other records of events at Cornell.

bioghist.head: ORGANIZATIONAL HISTORY
bioghist.p: The Cornell University News Service was formerly known as the Office of Public Relations, Public Relations and Information, and the News Bureau. It currently reports to the Vice President for University Relations.

scopecontent.head: COLLECTION DESCRIPTION
scopecontent.p: Includes correspondence, news press releases, notes, publicity material, newspaper clippings, distribution lists, administrative files, photographs, biographies, and other records of events at Cornell such as an Andrew Dickson White Commemorative Service, 1957; Cornell University Dinners; communism at Cornell; Olin Library Dedication, 1962; visit of Vice President Richard M. Nixon, 1956; installation of Cornell President Deane Waldo Malott; Festival of Contemporary Arts, 1950-1959; School of Industrial and Labor Relations dedication; Cornell Latin American Year, 1965-1966; International Student Conference, 1965; Cornell's centennial; and other events. Typescript and mimeographed press releases concerning faculty, students, and events at Cornell University. Audiotapes of radio programs and campus events, radio productions, movie films, and other records.

Photographs used by News Service and in Publications in the normal course of their operations. Contains photographs used by News Service throughout its history, spanning a wide range of subjects, which includes buildings, people, events, student activities, and other Cornell-relation miscellany.

odd.p: Photographic assignments done by Jill Peltzman are located in 4-3-15 Box 63.
See also Cornell University Relations and Public Information Office audio visual records collection #4-3-875: http://resolver.library.cornell.edu/cgi-bin/EADresolver?id=RMA00875.

Guestbooks include the signature of guests, where they live, where they were staying on campus during the week, and their class year. The books are filled with many important names from Cornell's early graduates and faculty. Names of graduates go back to some of the earliest Cornell classes, including the Class of 1870. Notable names include Davy Hoy, Simon Henry Gage, Robert Henry Treman, Frank A Barton, Sao-Ke Alfred Sze, Louis Agassiz Fuertes, Clark Sutherland Northup, and many others.
